WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.640
Hi, I'm Jamie and I'm going to talk about developing internal tools for multi-lingual

00:00:10.640 --> 00:00:15.200
teams, specifically teams that use Python and R.

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:19.680
To get started I want to talk about pizza. Imagine you're having a couple of friends

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:24.280
over for dinner and you need to prepare them something. The easiest thing to do is to prepare

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:29.160
them the same meal. However, they're both pretty fussy eaters. Do you make two entirely

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:35.000
different meals, with all the extra ingredients, prep time and aggravation? No, you make pizza,

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.200
because even if you make a margarita pizza for one friend and a Hawaiian for the other,

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:44.720
they still have the same base, the same core ingredients. What does pizza have to do with

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:50.680
R and Python? The prospect of developing a tool in both R and Python can feel like you're

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:56.119
about to prepare two entirely different meals. It's twice the effort, twice the cognitive

00:00:56.119 --> 00:01:01.680
load, and can take a lot more time. How can we take the principle of our pizza party,

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:06.639
that is, making two different meals with the same base, and apply it to developing bilingual

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:13.360
tools? This is a question I think about a lot in my job. I work at Bumble, we are the

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:18.959
company behind the dating and social networking apps, Badoo, Bumble and Fruits. My job is

00:01:18.959 --> 00:01:24.800
to develop internal packages for our data analysts. Most of our analysts work in Python,

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:30.080
however, some of our projects are done in R. This means some of our internal packages

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:36.440
are developed in both languages. But why do we need internal packages? Well, internal

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:42.680
packages can help to automate and standardise procedures that are specific to your organisation.

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:48.919
For example, an internal package might automatically apply company styling to a report, or enable

00:01:48.919 --> 00:01:55.239
a user to connect to an internal database in the correct way. To borrow from our studio

00:01:55.239 --> 00:02:00.580
global talk, internal packages are kind of like members of your organisation with specific

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:07.080
jobs to do. Why develop in both Python and R? The answer is simple. In a multilingual

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:12.520
organisation, we want everyone to follow the same internal procedures regardless of the

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:18.139
language that they're using. The question I will try to address today is what strategies

00:02:18.139 --> 00:02:24.500
can we use to make developing tools simultaneously with Python and R easier? In truth, this is

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:31.539
a very big topic with lots of branching ideas. Therefore, today, I will focus on three ideas

00:02:31.539 --> 00:02:38.259
that have helped me to develop bilingual tools. The first idea I want to talk about is building

00:02:38.259 --> 00:02:42.740
identical generic functions. But what is a generic function? Let's look at this from

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:48.779
the R perspective. Generic functions are very common in the R language. For example, functions

00:02:48.779 --> 00:02:54.500
like print, or summary, or tidy from the broom package. The really cool thing about generics

00:02:54.500 --> 00:02:58.380
is that they behave in different ways depending on the class of an object that is passed to

00:02:58.380 --> 00:03:05.339
them. Under the hood, this is achieved using a process called method dispatch. As an internal

00:03:05.339 --> 00:03:10.259
developer, you might want to build a package that uses custom internal classes, and you

00:03:10.259 --> 00:03:15.660
may want your users to be able to call methods like print or summary on them. In some cases,

00:03:15.660 --> 00:03:20.259
you may even want to define your own generic functions. Let's take a look at what generic

00:03:20.259 --> 00:03:24.779
functions look like in code. To do this, we will create a new package which will provide

00:03:24.779 --> 00:03:30.059
one function, say hello, and this will print a nice friendly greeting to an object that

00:03:30.059 --> 00:03:37.059
we pass to it. To start, we define our generic function, say hello, and in the function body,

00:03:37.059 --> 00:03:42.899
we make a call to use method, passing it the name of our generic as a string. And that's

00:03:42.899 --> 00:03:48.300
it, that's our generic. But now we need a class specific implementation of this function.

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:53.699
And to do this, let's make one for a data frame. And to do it, we will use dot notation,

00:03:53.699 --> 00:04:00.820
say hello dot data frame. And in this new function, we print a nice friendly greeting.

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:05.380
And now if you want to catch all implementations say hello, we will use the default pseudo

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:13.820
class, say hello dot default. Okay, now we know how our R package is going to work. We

00:04:13.820 --> 00:04:20.779
need a Python version. Can we write our Python version in the same way as our R version?

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:25.820
And the answer is yes. To do this, we're going to import single dispatch from the functuals

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:33.179
module. And unlike R, we actually start by defining our fallback method for say hello.

00:04:33.179 --> 00:04:38.260
And we decorate it with single dispatch. Now, if you're not familiar with decorators,

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:44.299
think of them as wrapper functions that change the behavior of a function. And now we're

00:04:44.299 --> 00:04:49.859
going to create a data frame implementation of say hello in Python, using a data frame

00:04:49.859 --> 00:04:54.579
object from the pandas library. And we do this with the register function. And here

00:04:54.579 --> 00:05:01.179
I am passing that data frame to the register function. And there we have it. But what have

00:05:01.179 --> 00:05:07.459
we actually achieved here? Well, we have two different tools, one in R, one in Python

00:05:07.459 --> 00:05:13.859
that have the same foundation, a say hello generic with a data frame implementation.

00:05:13.859 --> 00:05:19.579
So both of my packages work the same conceptually. This is good for end users, they get a similar

00:05:19.579 --> 00:05:26.899
API to work with regardless of whether they're using R or Python. But also my code is physically

00:05:26.899 --> 00:05:32.220
quite similar. So when I go and make a change in the Python version of my code, I know where

00:05:32.220 --> 00:05:38.779
to go and make that change in the R version of my code. So building identical generic

00:05:38.779 --> 00:05:44.579
functions is going to save me a lot of time and effort. The next idea I will talk about

00:05:44.579 --> 00:05:50.179
is identical error handling with classes. Let's look at this from the Python perspective.

00:05:50.179 --> 00:05:55.019
Now, if you're a Python user, you're probably familiar with these kinds of exceptions, far

00:05:55.019 --> 00:06:00.500
not found error, zero division error, and key error. Exceptions in Python are themselves

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:04.859
classes that inherit from other exception classes. And you can probably already tell

00:06:04.859 --> 00:06:10.619
that the names of these exceptions are quite descriptive, they form part of the error message.

00:06:10.619 --> 00:06:15.380
Now as an internal developer, you can create your own custom internal errors, you can give

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:20.820
them really descriptive names. And the error messages that they give can be as well specific

00:06:20.820 --> 00:06:28.059
as you want, even telling the user where to go for help if that error has been thrown.

00:06:28.059 --> 00:06:32.420
The powerful thing about exceptions in Python is that they can be handled explicitly. For

00:06:32.420 --> 00:06:36.820
example, with a try except statement, I asked Python to try running some code. And in the

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:42.059
event of a specific error, in this case, a far not found error, I can run an alternative

00:06:42.059 --> 00:06:48.260
block of code. This gives me maximum control over how my code handles failure.

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:56.100
Okay, so we're building a Python package, and we are handling errors in this way. But

00:06:56.100 --> 00:07:02.660
can we handle errors in the same way in our R packages? The answer is yes. But let's look

00:07:02.660 --> 00:07:08.420
at some basic error handling in R first.

00:07:08.420 --> 00:07:13.540
If you're an R user, you may have seen one of these two functions stop from base R and

00:07:13.540 --> 00:07:19.459
abort from the R line package. Both functions signal an error. And in R, if we want to handle

00:07:19.459 --> 00:07:24.579
errors in our code, we can use something like a try catch function. But notice here on the

00:07:24.579 --> 00:07:31.140
second line, the error handler is a function that will execute in response to any error.

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:35.779
It's not designed to handle a specific error. And this is a problem. I now have a lot less

00:07:35.779 --> 00:07:41.459
control over my code. And more importantly, my Python and R packages handle failure in

00:07:41.459 --> 00:07:49.779
very different ways. How can we overcome this? Well, the answer to this is within the

00:07:49.779 --> 00:07:56.579
abort function from Rlang. Let me illustrate this with an example. I'm going to create

00:07:56.579 --> 00:08:02.739
a new function abort credentials missing. And within called Rlang abort, I'm going to

00:08:02.739 --> 00:08:09.940
give a specific class name. Here it's error credentials missing. Now the really great

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:18.820
thing about error functions in R is that you can create an equivalent Python exception.

00:08:18.820 --> 00:08:24.179
So as an internal developer, you have your Python exceptions and you have your R error

00:08:24.179 --> 00:08:28.260
functions. They're one and the same. So when you make a change in one language, you know

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:34.099
where to make that change in the other language. But what have we gained by giving our error

00:08:34.099 --> 00:08:39.140
a class name? Well, let's go back to try catch. You can see here on the second line, I can

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:45.780
now write a specific error handler for my new error credentials missing. And now my

00:08:45.780 --> 00:08:52.659
Python package and my R package handle failure in the same way. I want to round off this

00:08:52.659 --> 00:08:58.900
section on errors by talking about error chaining. In essence, error chaining is throwing an

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:04.020
error in response to another error. One use for this is to give a high level context to

00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:11.380
a lower level error. Doing this in Python is very easy. For example, you can give your

00:09:11.380 --> 00:09:15.940
original error an alias. Here I'm giving it the alias E. And then I'm raising another

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:22.260
exception from that original exception. And this gives me a kind of double error message.

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:26.179
I get my original error and then Python tells me that this error caused another error.

00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:33.619
Can we emulate this in R? The answer is yes. Now the way that we're going to do this is we're

00:09:33.619 --> 00:09:40.020
going to use try fetch from the Rlang package instead of a try catch. And in my error handler,

00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:46.179
I'm going to pass my condition object to the abort function, specifically the parent argument.

00:09:49.460 --> 00:09:55.780
And here I get a kind of double error message. And there we have it. Our Python and R packages

00:09:55.780 --> 00:10:01.219
now conduct error chaining in the same way. The third idea I want to talk about is creating your

00:10:01.219 --> 00:10:07.859
own internal wrappers. But what is an internal wrapper? Well, it's a package written in one

00:10:07.859 --> 00:10:12.739
language that wraps functionality from another language. But why would you want to create your

00:10:12.739 --> 00:10:18.500
own internal wrapper? Well, imagine a scenario where a piece of functionality is available in

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:23.539
one language but not the other. A well-known example is a statistical model that's released

00:10:23.539 --> 00:10:28.979
as an R package but not a Python package. But you want all of your analysts to be able to access

00:10:28.979 --> 00:10:35.539
that functionality. Another scenario you might encounter is that both languages have their own

00:10:35.539 --> 00:10:40.260
implementation of a piece of functionality, like a statistical model, but maybe the underlying

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:47.700
computations aren't quite the same. And therefore, your analysts get different results. Okay, let's

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:52.419
kick this section off by looking at how we call Python from R. There are many ways to do this.

00:10:52.419 --> 00:10:58.659
My method of choice is the reticulate package. Reticulate gives you a number of different ways

00:10:58.659 --> 00:11:05.219
to call Python code in your R package. Let's look at a couple of examples. Now, the first example is

00:11:05.219 --> 00:11:10.580
importing Python modules into R. This works really well if the Python code you're trying to access

00:11:10.580 --> 00:11:17.299
is contained within a Python package. And to do this, I use the import function from reticulate.

00:11:17.299 --> 00:11:21.460
I give it the name of my module. Here, I'll call it pymodule, and I assign it to a variable.

00:11:22.179 --> 00:11:27.619
And now, I can access functions from that module using this dollar sign notation.

00:11:29.859 --> 00:11:35.219
Now, a really good tip for when you're doing this in an R package is to create a global reference

00:11:35.219 --> 00:11:41.460
to your Python package. And then you can use it throughout your code. Notice here, I'm not

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:48.099
actually importing anything yet. I'm going to specify how my Python module is imported

00:11:48.099 --> 00:11:55.059
in the onload function. This will execute when my R library is loaded. And here, I'm specifying

00:11:55.059 --> 00:12:00.419
delay load to true. And what this does is it gives my end user the ability to specify their

00:12:00.419 --> 00:12:07.780
own custom Python virtual environment to use with my package. Another way that you can use Python

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:13.380
code in your R package is to source Python files. This might work well if the code you're trying to

00:12:13.380 --> 00:12:20.580
access is contained within a Python script. To do this, I'm going to use a Python file. Here,

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:25.780
it's called add.py, which is contained in my R package. And inside that file, I define a new

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:32.900
function, add to. And now, I will use source Python from the reticulate package, and then I can access

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:42.900
the add to function. Okay. We've called Python from R. Now, let's call R from Python. Again,

00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:49.460
there are many ways to do this. My method of choice is the rpy2 package. rpy2 gives you a

00:12:49.460 --> 00:12:54.659
number of different ways to call R code from your Python package. Let's look at some examples.

00:12:56.580 --> 00:13:02.419
The first method is to import R libraries into Python. To do this, we're going to import the

00:13:02.419 --> 00:13:09.140
import R function from rpy2. And then, in this example, we're actually going to import base R

00:13:09.140 --> 00:13:14.340
itself, which we can import like any other library. To access a function from base R,

00:13:14.340 --> 00:13:18.500
we use this dot notation. Here, I'm accessing the sum function.

00:13:21.059 --> 00:13:23.780
Now, to use this function, I'm going to have to do a little bit of work.

00:13:24.979 --> 00:13:31.219
Sometimes, when you're using rpy2, you need to convert objects between R and Python. In this

00:13:31.219 --> 00:13:37.859
example, I need to convert my Python list into an R vector. I can do that using the int vector

00:13:37.940 --> 00:13:44.500
function from rpy2. You can check out the rpy2 documentation for more tips on object conversion.

00:13:46.340 --> 00:13:53.619
Another way to access R code from Python using rpy2 is to create new functions and access them

00:13:53.619 --> 00:13:59.380
from the R environment. This approach works really well when you have multiple computation steps that

00:13:59.380 --> 00:14:07.619
need to happen in R. Now, to do this, we're going to first import the R objects module from rpy2.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:13.299
We're then going to define our R code as a string. Here, I'm just creating a new function that

00:14:13.299 --> 00:14:22.500
returns one. I then execute that R code using the R function from R objects. And then, I can access

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:29.059
that new function using globalenv and assign it to a variable. And now, pyfunc is actually a

00:14:29.059 --> 00:14:34.820
function that I can execute. Now, a really great utility that rpy2 gives you is the ability to

00:14:34.820 --> 00:14:42.340
define a temporary package structure. Now, we can do this by importing the stap function

00:14:42.979 --> 00:14:52.580
from rpy2. And just like before, we store our R code as a string. And then, we use stap to execute

00:14:53.140 --> 00:14:59.059
that code. And then, we can access functions from that code using this dot notation.

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:05.619
So, this approach works really well when you are concerned about issues like namespace conflicts.

00:15:08.419 --> 00:15:13.299
Okay. Now, for the bad news. Cross-language wrappers have their own technical quirks and headaches.

00:15:14.659 --> 00:15:18.099
For example, you have twice the number of environments to think about.

00:15:18.099 --> 00:15:24.179
Your users will need to have access to both Python and R. And your packages will need to

00:15:24.419 --> 00:15:27.859
your packages will need to deal with the relevant dependencies.

00:15:28.659 --> 00:15:34.099
From personal experience, Reticulate is a lot more explicit about how it handles Python environments.

00:15:34.099 --> 00:15:38.580
Whereas, with rpy2, you need to do a little bit more of the work yourself.

00:15:40.900 --> 00:15:45.940
Now, another issue is object conversion. Sometimes, to work with cross-language wrappers,

00:15:45.940 --> 00:15:51.140
you need to handle the conversion of an object from one language to another, like you saw with rpy2.

00:15:51.380 --> 00:15:57.219
And a third issue are error messages. Sometimes, when an error occurs in the language that is being

00:15:57.219 --> 00:16:03.780
wrapped, the error message doesn't come through in its entirety, which can frustrate your efforts

00:16:03.780 --> 00:16:09.859
to create nice, helpful error messages. But with all this being said, cross-language wrappers are

00:16:09.859 --> 00:16:15.299
a really useful tool in your internal toolkit. They can deal with issues of missing functionality

00:16:15.619 --> 00:16:22.419
or inconsistent outputs between languages. And there we have it. Three different ways

00:16:22.419 --> 00:16:26.900
to build bilingual tools without having to design two entirely different solutions.

00:16:27.859 --> 00:16:32.900
The goal of each of these ideas is to make the development process and the maintenance process

00:16:32.900 --> 00:16:39.219
much easier for you. If you're an internal tool developer working in a bilingual organization,

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:44.739
I would encourage you to seek out these programming concepts and ideas that can

00:16:44.739 --> 00:16:52.419
help to bridge the gap between Python and R. Ultimately, the goal of this is to make your

00:16:52.419 --> 00:17:00.260
life as a developer much, much easier. Thank you for listening, and happy developing.

